## Chapter 17: Internationalization (i18n)

### 17.1 Setup

[lib/i18n.js](file:///d:/Projects/lib/i18n.js) initializes i18next with:
- `i18next-browser-languagedetector` — auto-detects browser language
- Default namespace: `translation`
- Default language: [en](file:///d:/Projects/lib/email.js#3-52)
- Fallback: English for missing translations

### 17.2 Available Languages

The system is structured to support multiple languages. Translation files are in the public directory.

### 17.3 Usage in Components

```javascript
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';

function MyComponent() {
  const { t } = useTranslation();
  return <h1>{t('nav.title')}</h1>;
}
```

### 17.4 Language Selector ([components/LanguageSelector.jsx](file:///d:/Projects/components/LanguageSelector.jsx))

A dropdown in both the nav bar and dashboard header. Lists available languages. On selection, calls `i18n.changeLanguage(code)` which re-renders all translated strings. Also available is `<GoogleTranslate />` as an alternative.

### 17.5 Translation Keys (Examples)

```
nav.title           → "Civic System"
nav.signIn          → "Sign In"
nav.signUp          → "Get Started"
nav.sidebar.dashboard → "Dashboard"
landing.hero        → "Report Issues. Track Progress. Build Better Cities."
landing.aiProcessing  → "AI Processing"
report.submit       → "Submit Report"
status.pending      → "Pending"
status.resolved     → "Resolved"
roles.citizen       → "Citizen"
roles.admin         → "Administrator"
faq.q1              → "How do I track my complaint?"
footer.copyright    → "© {year} CivicPulse. All rights reserved."
```

